[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Hello everybody and welcome to this course!  Before talking about the course itself, I would like to introduce myself a little bit. I started playing chess when I was very little. I was only 5 years old when I learned how to move the pieces, and I instantly fell in love with the game. After that, I started going to the chess club in my city (Granada). I met a lot of good friends over there. As you guys know, the atmosphere in the chess world is amazing. So after that, I began to play in some tournaments, improving my level, and I have been an active player ever since. Finally, when I was 28 years old, I got my GM title.  When I was 17-18 years old, I had to stop playing in tournaments for a bit. I started to study at the University and graduated as a civil engineer. After that, I did an MSc in mathematical modeling in engineering, and finally, I did my Ph.D. in applied mathematics in Germany. But during my holiday time, instead of going somewhere else, I was always trying to play chess tournaments.  During all these years, I have participated in different European leagues (Spanish, German, Swedish, Danish, Italian, French, and Portuguese). I was the runner-up in the Spanish National Championship in 2018.  Besides playing, I have been a commentator since 2014 for chess24, mainly in Spanish but also in English. It is something that I really enjoy, trying to share the little things I know about the game and trying to entertain people by having some fun.  As a trainer, I was the coach of Puerto Rico in the last Olympiad in Chennai. I always had many students as well, and it is something that I really enjoy too. As an author, I have been creating a lot of content and videos since 2014, mainly for chess24. Now I am extremely happy to have joined the Chessable family, where I will be bringing a lot of courses in the following years.  Finally, it is time to talk about the course, the Lifetime Repertoire based on the Sicilian with 2...Nc6. In the last couple of years, my repertoire for Black has become much more solid, mainly playing 1...e5 against 1.e4 when facing strong opponents. Sometimes it is hard to play for a win when employing such super solid variations with Black, so I asked myself, 'What should I play when I need or want to go for the win?'  My answer was a Sicilian, and then I started looking for different alternatives. This is how I came up with the Kalashnikov, a good surprising weapon that leads to very complex and unbalanced positions, where if we have done our homework and know our theory, we have great probabilities of coming out of the opening with a good position or even an advantage.  Obviously, the various references to other Chessable courses or books have been mentioned throughout the course, and here is a brief overview:    Play the Open Sicilian  by GM Miguel Santos  King’s Kalashnikov Sicilian  by GM Daniel King  The Open Sicilian: A Champion’s Guide  by GM Ivan Saric  Playing 1.e4: Sicilian Main Lines  by GM John Shaw  The Rossolimo Sicilian  by GM Victor Bologan  Beating the Anti-Sicilians  by GM Vassilios Kotronias  Keep It Simple 1.e4  by IM Christof Sielecki  
I am bringing you a lot of novelties and fresh ideas, and we also deviate from Danny King's variation in the main line, offering you a second fresh alternative. In every variation, I have checked the different recipes that other authors give, and we have found an improvement or lines that they do not analyze, so we increase the chance that our opponent is not prepared in all those variations.  I have prepared for this course with a lot of passion and hard work, and I already employed this repertoire in many of my classical games(you can check the database!), so I hope you guys can benefit from this course and analysis as well.  Lots of love from Spain!  GM Pepe Cuenca.} 1. --
