7. Bg4 {It is always nice to provoke f3 because the dark squares become a little bit weaker. It is a small and difficult subtlety but a nice one!} 
8. f3
8. Be6
9. Ne3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Nb4 {This move has been tried by the Indian prodigies Nihal Sarin and Praggnanandhaa. It is the most concrete move, aiming to neutralize White's initiative by force.} 
11. Ncd5 {This should never be played if White has to recapture with the pawn.} 
11. Nbxd5
12. exd5
12. Bd7 {Black took over inFogarasi-Berczes, Budapest 2005. The bishop on c4 is very clumsy and the diagonal has been closed by the white pawn on d5. Black's play is easier thanks to the pawn majority on the kingside.} 
