1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!To begin with, we will look at different moves than5.Nb5. They are mostly played at the club level and do not pose a threat to Black's existence in the Kalashnikov. There is not really any theory, so I recommend you to go through the lines to get a feeling for the arising positions instead of memorizing (as remembering the lines after5.Nb5is much more important!).} 
5. Nb3 {The knight is a little out of place on b3, so this move is strange. Still, it is probably the best alternative to Nb5 and it has been tried by Nepo a few times.} 
5. Nf6
6. Bg5 {The best move for White, pinning our knight.} 
6. Be7 {We reinforce the threat on the e4-pawn.} 
7. Bxf6
7. Bxf6
8. Nc3
8. O-O
9. Bc4 {White has control over the d5-square but has paid a high price for it: the dark-squared bishop. The position is around equal but playable for both sides. You should try to play some games to understand this kind of position.} 
9. d6
10. Nd5
10. Bg5
11. O-O
11. Be6 {The standard way to play this kind of position. We want to go ...Ne7 next and fight for the d5-square.11...Kh8is King's recommendation in his Kalashnikov course and also decent, trying to playwith ...f5.} 
