10. Nd5 {The most logical and also the most critical.} 
10. Bxd5 {It is important to take with the bishop and put pressure on the d5-pawn.After10...Nxd5?!11.exd5Bf512.Bd3Bxd313.Qxd3⩲, White is quite fast on the queenside, and we have not even castled yet.} 
11. exd5
11. Nf6
12. g3 {This pawn sacrifice is the recommendation of Saric. White wants to get a strong grip on the light squares after Black takes on d5. I think I have found a nice solution for Black's problems here.} 
12. Nbxd5
13. Bg2
13. Nc7 {The knight is safer on c7. Next, we want to play ...e4 and ...d5 to increase our control on the light squares. After13...Nb614.Ne3, White hasalso a5 ideas, and we are not in time to mobilize our center.} 
14. O-O
14. e4 {Now White has to do something quickly or will be down a pawn with no compensation. The games get a forcing nature, but the ideas are quite simple and you do not have to memorize everything.} 
15. f3 {A bit of an odd move here.15.a5is probably the strongest continuation, but quite difficult to understand in an OTB game. However, we have it covered, of course.} 
15. d5
16. Ne3
16. h5 {Avoiding Ng4 ideas. We are already better.} 
