[Black "Closed Sicilian 3.g3 − 6.Be3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. g3 {The Closed Sicilian is not dangerous from a theoretical point of view, and there are many ways to equalize, but it is important to know one good setup.} 
3. g6 {I really like the fianchetto versus the Closed Sicilian. The bishop on g7 will be our best minor piece.} 
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. d3
5. Rb8 {One of the advantages of playing ...Nc6 on move 2 (something Najdorf players cannot do!) is having this quick ...Rb8. I have always felt that gaining space on the queenside as quickly as possible is one of the strongest ways to meet this fianchetto setup.} 
6. Be3
6. b5 {We do not need to defend the c5-pawn just yet.} 
7. Bxc5
7. Qa5
8. Be3
8. b4
9. Nce2
9. Bxb2 {We gain back our pawn.} 
10. Rb1
10. b3+ {There are alternatives, but this makes things clearer. We should remember the following forced sequence.} 
11. Bd2
11. bxc2
12. Qxc2
12. Nb4 {We keep playing powerful active moves.} 
13. Qb3
13. Qa3
14. Nf4
14. Qxb3
15. axb3
15. Be5 {The position is symmetrical, but we have a small initiative.} 
