[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Closed Sicilian 3.Nge2"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian 3.Nge2 Nd4 4.b3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nge2 {A tricky move order for us Kalashnikov players. Fortunately, we have a concrete solution to this line.} 
3. Nd4 {If the knight stood on f3 instead of e2, Bc4 would be good for White, but now this option does not exist anymore. After Nxd4, the critical move, the position usually gets quite crazy, and I think we have very good chances in the ensuing complications.3...e5is our reaction whenthe knight is on f3, but here the knight does not block the f-pawn and White can play f4 quite quickly. Maybe this is playable, but it is certainly a worse version for us.} 
4. b3
4. g6 {As against2.b3, we develop the bishop on the long diagonal to oppose White's bishop.} 
5. Nxd4 {White can force us to take with the pawn, but it is not very dangerous.} 
5. cxd4
6. Ne2
6. Bg7
7. Bb2
7. e5
8. c3
8. Nf6 {Preparing castling and keeping an eye on the e4-pawn. True, White can win a pawn on d4, but that comes with a price tag: we will get the initiative in return.} 
9. cxd4 {If White tries to defend the pawn first with9.f3, we play in a similar fashion to the line at hand:9...O-O10.cxd4exd411.Bxd4Re8followed by ...d5 and a better position already despite the material deficit.} 
9. exd4
10. Bxd4
10. O-O
11. d3 {This looks normal, but with the king still in the center, White risks getting mated.} 
11. d5
12. f3 {12.e5is way too optimistic. Following12...Ng413.f4f6!White is suffering big time being underdeveloped and overextended.} 
12. Qe7 {Black has more than enough compensation here. The king is stuck in the middle of the board and White's center is not as solid as it looks. The machine already says Black is much better, and the immediate threat is ...dxe4 followed by ...Rd8.} 
