[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nge2 {A tricky move order for us Kalashnikov players. Fortunately, we have a concrete solution to this line.} 
3. Nd4 {If the knight stood on f3 instead of e2, Bc4 would be good for White, but now this option does not exist anymore. After Nxd4, the critical move, the position usually gets quite crazy, and I think we have very good chances in the ensuing complications.3...e5is our reaction whenthe knight is on f3, but here the knight does not block the f-pawn and White can play f4 quite quickly. Maybe this is playable, but it is certainly a worse version for us.} 
4. d3 {This is a slower approach compared to4.Nxd4.} 
4. e5 {Almost never played, but fortifying our d4-knight is the easiest way to get an equal position.} 
5. Nxd4
5. cxd4
6. Nd5
6. Ne7 {Instead,6...Nf6hands White the option of7.Bg5, which threatens to ruin our structure, and7...Be78.Nxe7leaves us without the bishop pair.} 
7. Bg5
7. h6 {Not falling for7...f68.Qh5+.} 
8. Bxe7 {8.Bf6may seem troublesome but in reality, there is nothing to worry about if we don't take the poisoned bishop and calmly continue to develop with8...d6.  In fact, if you are feeling funky,8...Qa5+leads to an interesting queen investment. After9.b4Nxd510.bxa5Bb4+11.c3Bxc3+12.Ke2Nxf6, the positional sacrifice could pose White some developing issues, while Black's moves arenatural: ...O-O, ...d5, etc. Not for the faint of heart though...} 
8. Bxe7 {We will expel or take White's knight after ...b6, ...Bb7, and the position will be completely equal.} 
