[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nc3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nge2 {A tricky move order for us Kalashnikov players. Fortunately, we have a concrete solution to this line.} 
3. Nd4 {If the knight stood on f3 instead of e2, Bc4 would be good for White, but now this option does not exist anymore. After Nxd4, the critical move, the position usually gets quite crazy, and I think we have very good chances in the ensuing complications.3...e5is our reaction whenthe knight is on f3, but here the knight does not block the f-pawn and White can play f4 quite quickly. Maybe this is playable, but it is certainly a worse version for us.} 
4. Nxd4
4. cxd4
5. Nb5
5. e5
6. Qh5 {The only critical try. From a static point of view, we are completely fine because we have firm central control, so White should bother us with concrete play.} 
6. d6
7. Bc4
7. g6
8. Qf3
8. Nf6 {The most ambitious continuation.8...Be6is also possible, but after something like9.Bxe6fxe610.Qb3Qd711.c3, White's position is more comfortable. After the text move, we intend to finish developmentwith ...Bg7 and ...O-O. If we achieve that, we will be more than fine, so White should keep playing in a very concrete way.} 
9. Nc7+ {This move is a very natural novelty.} 
9. Qxc7
10. Qxf6
10. Qxc4 {Our idea.10...Rg811.d3would lead to an unpleasant position for Black. Here, we will lose an exchange, but we will always have compensation thanks to our bishop pair and the terriblebishop on c1, which is a very problematic piece for White.} 
11. Qxh8
11. d3 {The key move, threatening ...Qxe4+.} 
12. O-O {The only decent move. After12.cxd3?Qxd313.f3Be6, we are an exchange down, but our attack is decisive. For example14.Kf2Rc815.Qxh7d5!16.exd5Bxd517.Re1Bc5+18.Kg3Qd4–+.} 
12. Qxe4 {12...dxc2?13.d3!followed by Bh6 is something we do not want. After taking on e4, we are threatening to take on c2, because after d3 we have at least ...Qh4, stopping Bh6.} 
13. cxd3
13. Qd4 {A very strong move! The bishop on c1 is now a nightmare piece and White is kind of paralyzed. After13...Qxd3, White has14.a4followed by Ra3.} 
14. a4 {A good move − the rook can now be developed via a3 in case of emergency.} 
14. h5 {We defend the h7-pawn.} 
15. Ra3
15. Be6
16. Rc3
16. Kd7
17. b3
17. Qf4 {We keep playing against the c1-bishop. The position is very complex and I like Black's chances.} 
