3. Nd4 {If the knight stood on f3 instead of e2, Bc4 would be good for White, but now this option does not exist anymore. After Nxd4, the critical move, the position usually gets quite crazy, and I think we have very good chances in the ensuing complications.3...e5is our reaction whenthe knight is on f3, but here the knight does not block the f-pawn and White can play f4 quite quickly. Maybe this is playable, but it is certainly a worse version for us.} 
4. Nxd4
4. cxd4
5. Ne2
5. e5
6. c3 {The only critical move, challenging our center.} 
6. d5 {Counterattacking in the center.} 
7. exd5
7. Qxd5
8. cxd4
8. exd4
9. Qa4+ {Do not worry, we didn't blunder the d4-pawn for nothing!} 
9. Bd7
10. Qxd4
10. Nf6 {More precise than taking immediately, as we do not want to activate White's pieces.} 
11. Qxd5
11. Nxd5 {We are a pawn down, but the extra pawn on d2 is hardly felt at the moment and we will see that we have equal play in all lines.} 
12. Nc3
12. Nb4
13. Kd1
13. Bc5
14. f3
14. O-O {White is playing with fire here.} 
