5. Bc4 {Nowadays this is played even more than the older main lines with5.d4.} 
5. Nb6
6. Bb3
6. d5
7. exd6
7. Qxd6
8. O-O
8. c4 {This is a double-edged move: in some positions the pawn restricts White's army and is very strong, while in others it can become a weakness after b3 and Na3. I believe that with precise play, we can make this principled move work.} 
9. Bc2
9. Bg4 {The most principled move, developing the bishop to its most active square. Now White has a fundamental choice to make: playing h3 or not. The first time you look at this, maybe it does not seem so important, but actually, we play in two completely different ways against each approach.} 
10. h3
10. Bh5
11. Re1
11. O-O-O
12. b3 {I have chosen this move to be the main line because it was recommended by Christiansen in his recent Alapin course for White.} 
12. Qf6
13. Na3 {The critical move, which leads to very forced play.After13.Be4Ne514.g4Nxf3+15.Qxf3Qxf316.Bxf3Bg617.Na3e618.Nxc4Nxc419.bxc4Bd3!=, we are going to recover the pawn with a good position.13.bxc4Bxf314.Qxf3Qxf315.gxf3Nxc4=is equal.} 
13. Nd5 {13...Bxf314.Qxf3Qxf315.gxf3cxb316.axb3is not ideal for us, as White's center looks dangerous.} 
14. Nxc4
14. b5 {The most trusted move in the correspondence chess world, but note that Stockfish also shows 0.00 after14...Nxc315.dxc3Rxd116.Bxd1g5!(giving some air to our queen)17.Bxg5Qg7, with a completely crazy position.} 
15. Nb2 {15.Nce5Nxc316.dxc3Rxd117.Bxd1Nxe518.Rxe5Bxf319.Rc5+Kd720.Bxf3e621.Bg5Qxf322.gxf3Bxc5=is equal.15.Ne3Nxc3is a much better version of things for us now that White does not have Bg5.} 
15. Nxc3
16. dxc3
16. Rxd1
17. Bxd1
17. Qxc3 {17...e6is also possible, and in general, concrete theoretical knowledge is not necessary here. The position is 0.00 according to the machine in many different ways. We are material up, but our king is not too well-protected. Of course, in OTB chess anything can happen here.} 
