[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 − 6.Nd2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nc3 {The third most popular move after3.d4and3.Bb5. This line leads to calmer play, and we should be ready for a positional battle.} 
3. e5 {Stopping d4. We weaken the d5-square, but we get easy development, and in the long run, ...f5 can give us counterplay.3...g6is a decent alternative now that White cannot play the Maróczy, but I think3...e5is simpler.} 
4. Bc4
4. Be7 {The immediate4...Nf6would be met by5.Ng5, so we prepare it with a useful move.} 
5. d3
5. d6 {5...Nf6allows the very dangerous6.Ng5O-O7.h4!While Black is not lost there, we do not need to allow such an attack.} 
6. Nd2
6. Nf6
7. Nf1 {White wants to control d5 with all the forces available.} 
7. Bg4 {It is always nice to provoke f3 because the dark squares become a little bit weaker. It is a small and difficult subtlety but a nice one!} 
8. Qd2 {This is possible, but the queen is obviously misplaced on d2.} 
8. Nd7
9. Ne3
9. Bg5 {Before bringing the light-squared bishop back home, we improve our dark-squared bishop.} 
10. O-O
10. Be6
11. Qd1
11. O-O {White has very little in this kind of position. Yes, our d5-square is weak, but we are prepared to fight for it with moves like ...Nb6 or ...Ne7, and if White puts a piece on d5, usually lots of exchanges follow. Slowly preparing ...f5 with moves like ...Kh8 and ...g6 is a good idea.  You do not need to memorize anything here, but it is useful to look at how correspondence games develop to get a feeling for the position.} 
12. Ned5 {12.a4Nb613.Ba2Bxa214.Rxa2Nc8!?15.Ra1N8e716.Ncd5Nxd517.Nxd5Bxc118.Rxc1Ne7=½-½ Bucek-Hybl, ICCF email 2010.} 
12. Bxc1
13. Qxc1
13. Nd4
14. Ne3 {14.a4f515.f3f4,planning to continue with ...Kh8 and ...g5, was seen in ½-½ Kilichenko-Pecka, ICCF email 2015.} 
14. Qg5
15. f3
15. Nb6
16. b3
16. h5 {Gaining space on the kingside.} 
17. a4
17. h4 {Black equalized in ½-½ Steiger-Ketelhoehn, ICFF 2019.} 
