14. Bxd5
14. Bxd5
15. Qxe5
15. Bc6 {15...Be6was seen in a correspondence game, but Ifeel c6 is the best square for the bishop: it supports ...b5 and also keeps an eye on White's kingside. This is very similar to a Marshall: for the pawn, we have the bishop pair and active play.} 
16. Be3
16. Bd6
17. Qh5
17. f5 {Taking away the e4-square from White's knight in order to be able to push ...b5 next.} 
18. Rae1
18. b5 {White cannot convert the extra pawn in a position like this.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Sicilian 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 − 6.Nd2 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nc3 {The third most popular move after3.d4and3.Bb5. This line leads to calmer play, and we should be ready for a positional battle.} 
3. e5 {Stopping d4. We weaken the d5-square, but we get easy development, and in the long run, ...f5 can give us counterplay.3...g6is a decent alternative now that White cannot play the Maróczy, but I think3...e5is simpler.} 
4. Bc4
4. Be7 {The immediate4...Nf6would be met by5.Ng5, so we prepare it with a useful move.} 
5. d3
5. d6 {5...Nf6allows the very dangerous6.Ng5O-O7.h4!While Black is not lost there, we do not need to allow such an attack.} 
6. Nd2
6. Nf6
7. Nf1 {White wants to control d5 with all the forces available.} 
7. Bg4 {It is always nice to provoke f3 because the dark squares become a little bit weaker. It is a small and difficult subtlety but a nice one!} 
8. f3
8. Be6
9. Ne3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Nb4 {This move has been tried by the Indian prodigies Nihal Sarin and Praggnanandhaa. It is the most concrete move, aiming to neutralize White's initiative by force.} 
11. Qe2 {Prophylaxis against ...d5 (our e5-pawn will be hanging in some lines). Nevertheless, we can push11...d5anyway.} 
11. d5
12. exd5
12. Nfxd5
13. Nexd5
13. Nxd5
14. Bd2 {This was the move chosen by Jumabayev in his game against Pragg. I think the strongest is just to reinforce our position with the simple ...Re8.} 
14. Re8
15. Bxd5
15. Bxd5
16. Qxe5
16. Bc6 {This is a better version of14.Bxd5for Black, becausethe Bd2 and ...Re8 inclusion favors us.} 
