[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Nc3 {The third most popular move after3.d4and3.Bb5. This line leads to calmer play, and we should be ready for a positional battle.} 
3. e5 {Stopping d4. We weaken the d5-square, but we get easy development, and in the long run, ...f5 can give us counterplay.3...g6is a decent alternative now that White cannot play the Maróczy, but I think3...e5is simpler.} 
4. Bc4
4. Be7 {The immediate4...Nf6would be met by5.Ng5, so we prepare it with a useful move.} 
5. d3
5. d6 {5...Nf6allows the very dangerous6.Ng5O-O7.h4!While Black is not lost there, we do not need to allow such an attack.} 
6. O-O {The most natural continuation and the most played too.} 
6. Nf6
7. Ng5 {The most common move, preparing to launch the f-pawn!} 
7. O-O
8. f4
8. Bg4 {Developing with tempo.} 
9. Qe1
9. exf4
10. Bxf4
10. Nd4 {Now White has a choice between11.Qf2and11.Qd2, and we play in different ways against each move.} 
11. Qd2 {Compared to the11.Qf2variation, here we can play ...h6. See the note on the previous trainable for a more detailed explanation.} 
11. h6
12. Nf3
12. Nxf3+
13. gxf3
13. Bh3
14. Kh1 {This is a dangerous try, as White's pieces have a lot of attacking potential.} 
14. Bxf1
15. Rxf1
15. Kh7 {Defending against Bxh6.} 
16. Qg2
16. Ne8 {A very important move! The best defensive setup is to put the bishop on f6 and the knight on e6. White has compensation for the exchange thanks to the active pieces and the g-file, but we have enough resources to maintain the balance.} 
