[White "8) Rossolimo 3.Bb5 e6 − Various 4th Moves"]
[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 e6 4.Bxc6 bxc6 5.b3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Bb5
3. e6 {This is the line I am going to recommend. It leads to complex and unbalanced positions where we will be able to play for a win. The main idea is to play ...Nge7 on the next move, so we can recapture with the knight on c6.} 
4. Bxc6 {The only chance White gets to ruin our structure.} 
4. bxc6 {Note that we do not play4...dxc6. This move makes sense when we play3...g6because the bishop has active prospectson the c8-h3 diagonal, but with the pawn on e6, the bishop can become dead very easily!} 
5. b3 {This is a serious alternative to5.d3that was tried by Anand against Gelfand in the 2012 World Championship match.The a1-h8 diagonal is important in this position, so White's move makes quite some sense.} 
5. Ne7 {There are alternatives, like5...e5, which was tried by Gelfand in the match, but we stick to our normal move.} 
6. Bb2
6. d6 {This is the most dynamic move.6...f6is typical, but the positions after7.Nh4seemed a little bit unpleasant.} 
7. e5 {Otherwise, we push ...e5.} 
7. Nf5 {Th f5-square is a good outpost for our knight, as it defends g7 and it controls the key square f5. The first time I looked at this I was a little bit skeptical about Black's position because of the pawn structure that ensues after exd6, but after looking at it more deeply, I have realized that although the pawns are weak, they also control lots of central squares like d5 and d4.} 
8. Qe2
8. f6 {Very ambitious, we want to control the center.8...d5is not really an option from a human perspective, as we end up in a bad version of a reversed Nimzo-Indian.} 
9. exf6
9. gxf6
10. g4
10. Ng7 {The engine is a little bit skeptical about this at first, but at good depths, it understands that Black's center and bishops provide sufficient play despite the lack of development. If we manage to survive, we have a very good chance to win the game.} 
