5. Ne7 {There are alternatives, but this is very logical. If we manage to play ...Ng6-e5 and White does not get immediate play, then we will stand very well with our bishop pair and our central control.} 
6. h4 {Prophylaxis against ...Ng6, and we should take this idea seriously.} 
6. d6
7. e5 {White breaks our pawn structure. This would be bad for us after a move like6.Nbd2instead of6.h4. Here,the pawn on h4 will be misplaced and we will get nice counterplay.} 
7. f6 {This move has never been tried and is the easiest solution.} 
8. exd6
8. Nf5 {f5 is always the best square for the knight in these structures, as it has access to d4.} 
9. Na3
9. e5
10. Nc4
10. Bxd6
11. Nxd6+
11. Qxd6
12. b3
12. O-O
13. Ba3
13. Qd5 {We have seen similar positions in the5.b3lines, and the strangepawn on h4 only makes them more comfortable for Black.} 
