[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 e6 − 5.d3 Ne7 6.h4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Bb5
3. e6 {This is the line I am going to recommend. It leads to complex and unbalanced positions where we will be able to play for a win. The main idea is to play ...Nge7 on the next move, so we can recapture with the knight on c6.} 
4. Bxc6 {The only chance White gets to ruin our structure.} 
4. bxc6 {Note that we do not play4...dxc6. This move makes sense when we play3...g6because the bishop has active prospectson the c8-h3 diagonal, but with the pawn on e6, the bishop can become dead very easily!} 
5. d3 {The main move by far.} 
5. Ne7 {There are alternatives, but this is very logical. If we manage to play ...Ng6-e5 and White does not get immediate play, then we will stand very well with our bishop pair and our central control.} 
6. h4 {Prophylaxis against ...Ng6, and we should take this idea seriously.} 
6. d6
7. h5
7. e5
8. h6 {Gaining more space is the most logical continuation.} 
8. Bg4 {Moiseenko won a model game after8...Ng6, but immediately pinning White's knight is probably the most precise reaction.} 
9. hxg7
9. Bxg7
10. Bh6 {Exchanging our bishop pair is a good idea for White.} 
10. Bxh6
11. Rxh6
11. Ng6
12. Nbd2
12. d5 {A nice novelty! Gelfand got into trouble in an online blitz game playing natural moves like ...Qf6-g7. We should create tension in the center instead.} 
13. Qe2
13. Nf4
14. Qf1
14. Bxf3 {Continuing to play in a dynamic fashion.} 
15. gxf3
15. Qg5 {This is the start of a very nice double pawn sacrifice.} 
16. Rxc6
16. d4
17. Rxc5
17. h5 {The key idea behind our play: the h-pawn, supported by the magnificent knight on f4, is very powerful.} 
