5. Ne7 {There are alternatives, but this is very logical. If we manage to play ...Ng6-e5 and White does not get immediate play, then we will stand very well with our bishop pair and our central control.} 
6. Nbd2 {I feel this is one of the most dangerous tries. White stays flexible.} 
6. f6 {6...Ng6was the best move against 6.O-O, but here it runs into7.h4!h58.e5, when Black's position is quite uncomfortable because the knighton d2 reaches very quickly the key square c4.6...Qc7!?is a perfectly viable alternative, and Gelfand got a good position with it against Anand in Leon 2022, but I prefer6...f6because it leads to very interesting positions.} 
7. Nh4 {If we are allowed to play ...e5 in good conditions we are better, so White has to play in a very concrete way.} 
7. d5 {7...e58.f4!exf49.e5!is a very dangerous computer idea that we should avoid.} 
8. f4 {The critical move, stopping ...e5. It is important no note that8.e5is nicely answered by8...Qc7!9.exf6Qe5+!} 
8. c4 {Following Gelfand is almost always a good idea in the opening, and this position is no exception! We want to open the position for our bishops, even at the cost of a pawn.} 
9. dxc4
9. Qb6 {Our queen stands very well on b6.} 
10. Qf3 {This was Esipenko's choice in his game against Gelfand and it is also Stockfish's preferred move.10.Qe2Ba6is a better version for us with the queenpinned on e2.} 
10. Rg8 {Again, the mysterious rook move that happened in the game is the strongest one! Actually, it is not so mysterious: we want to play ...g5, trapping White's knight.} 
11. Qf2 {This looks very logical, trying to castle, but Black's position is of positional nature...} 
11. Qxf2+
12. Kxf2
12. h6 {The endgame is very comfortable for us with our big center and the bishop pair. The extra pawn is not felt at the moment.} 
