11. Qc7 {We can also start with11...c5, the move order is not so important.} 
12. Be3
12. c5
13. f4 {White needs to gain space on the kingside.} 
13. Bb7 {This is the kind of position that we need to understand in order to play this line. White has more space and is more comfortable at the moment, but we are quite solid and have dynamic counterplay with the ...f5 and ...d5 breaks. Another typical plan is to play ...d6, ...Bf6, and ...Ne7-c6-d4.} 
14. g3 {This move prepares the h4 advance to bother our g6-knight.} 
