[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. Bb5
3. e6 {This is the line I am going to recommend. It leads to complex and unbalanced positions where we will be able to play for a win. The main idea is to play ...Nge7 on the next move, so we can recapture with the knight on c6.} 
4. O-O
4. Nge7
5. Re1 {This is the main move − now the bishop has a safe retreat: the f1-square.} 
5. Nd4 {This is the move that scores best for Black here, and hopefully, it will come as a slight surprise to your opponents. I think it is a very logical way of playing, making room for our e7-knight. After analyzing it deeply I do not think it is worse than the main lines that start with5...a6.} 
6. Nxd4
6. cxd4
7. d3 {The idea with d3 is not to immediately challenge our pawn's center. White wants to play on the kingside with moves like Nd2, Qh5, f4, Nf3, etc.} 
7. a6
8. Ba4
8. b5
9. Bb3
9. Nc6 {We focus on completing development with natural moves.} 
10. Nd2
10. Bb7
11. f4 {This is the recommendation that is given in  Keep it simple 1.e4  by IM Christof Sielecki.} 
11. Qc7
12. Nf3 {Christof evaluates this position as slightly better for White. Stockfish 15 tells us that Black is perfectly fine though.} 
12. Bd6
13. e5
13. Bc5
14. Ng5 {White wants to bring the knight to e4 and at the same time free the d1-h5 diagonal for the queen. This was seen in 1-0 Isgandarova-Badelka, Riga 2017, but Black is much better after ...Ne7.} 
14. Ne7
15. Ne4
15. Nf5 {White struggles to develop the queenside. Our light-squared bishop has become a monster, as a result of White having played13.e5.} 
