3. e6 {This is the line I am going to recommend. It leads to complex and unbalanced positions where we will be able to play for a win. The main idea is to play ...Nge7 on the next move, so we can recapture with the knight on c6.} 
4. O-O
4. Nge7
5. Re1 {This is the main move − now the bishop has a safe retreat: the f1-square.} 
5. Nd4 {This is the move that scores best for Black here, and hopefully, it will come as a slight surprise to your opponents. I think it is a very logical way of playing, making room for our e7-knight. After analyzing it deeply I do not think it is worse than the main lines that start with5...a6.} 
6. Nxd4
6. cxd4
7. c3 {Challenging our pawn is the most critical move.} 
7. a6
8. Bf1
8. Nc6
9. b4 {Expansion on the queenside is the best plan for White.} 
9. Bd6 {The main move is9...Be7and it was the choice of Carlsen in a game against MVL, but I think we can develop the bishop to a more active square. Praggnanandhaa has played this way two times.} 
10. Bb2
10. dxc3
11. dxc3 {The critical move.} 
11. Qc7 {White has now three different ways of protecting the h2-pawn. All of them lead to slightly different positions and it is not clear which one is best.} 
12. Qh5 {This was the move chosen by Ter Sahakyan. The queen defends h2 and is well placed on h5 because ...g6 is usually too weakening.} 
12. O-O
13. Nd2 {13.a3Be514.Nd2b5is a transposition to the 13.Nd2 move order.} 
13. b5 {Stopping Nc4.} 
14. a4 {Whenever our pawn is on b5, this move should be checked.} 
14. Bb7 {Prioritizing development, Black sacrifices a pawn. If at some point White decides to take the pawn on b5, the idea is to counterattack with ...f5, opening the big diagonal for our monster on b7.} 
15. axb5
15. axb5
16. Nf3
16. Rxa1
17. Bxa1
17. h6 {Stopping Ng5 moves. White can take the b5-pawn, but we get sufficient play again.} 
18. Qxb5 {18.Bxb5Ra8with compensation thanks tothe ...Ra2 and ...Ne5 ideas.} 
18. Ne5
19. Nxe5
19. Bxe5
20. g3
20. Ra8 {Our activity provides sufficient compensation for the pawn.} 
