[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!In this chapter, we will look at different moves than5.Nb5. They are mostly played at the club level and do not pose a threat to Black's existence in the Kalashnikov. There is not really any theory, so I recommend you to go through the lines to get a feeling for the arising positions instead of memorizing (as remembering the lines after5.Nb5is much more important!).} 
5. Ne2 {A playable sideline, but of course, this is not going to refute the Kalasnikhov!} 
5. Nf6
6. Nbc3
6. Bc5 {This position can also be reached from a Sveshnikov move order.} 
7. Ng3 {White wants to develop the light-squared bishop.} 
7. O-O {I feel this is the best move, keeping our options open.7...d6was played by Wang Hao against Topalov recently, but it allows8.Na4!when if we do not want to lose the bishop pair we have to play8...Bb4+9.c3Ba510.b4Bc711.Be2with a playable position, but I believe White has some chances for an edge.After7...O-O, the8.Na4idea is no longer working in view of8...Qa5+9.c3and now Black canretreat the bishop to e7, with a much better position given the stranded knight on a4.} 
8. Be2 {White has played this way in some games, but it does not look very impressive.} 
8. Bb4 {We can afford to waste a tempo on this move since White can no longer take back on c3 with the knight, thus enabling ...d5.} 
9. O-O
9. Bxc3
10. bxc3
10. d5 {I would already pick Black here.} 
