1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!In this chapter, we will look at different moves than5.Nb5. They are mostly played at the club level and do not pose a threat to Black's existence in the Kalashnikov. There is not really any theory, so I recommend you to go through the lines to get a feeling for the arising positions instead of memorizing (as remembering the lines after5.Nb5is much more important!).} 
5. Nf3 {I do not get this move at all. We can get a good position with simple moves.} 
5. Nf6
6. Bg5 {This line is decent with the knight on b3, but here we have the extra option of going ...Qa5+.} 
6. Qa5+ {Forcing the bishop to retreat. After7.Bd2Qb6,we are the ones playing for an advantage, with ...Bc5 coming next.} 
