[White "13) Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.N1c3 − Introduction"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.N1c3 − 8.Nd5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. N1c3
6. a6
7. Na3
7. Be6 {7...Be7is King's recommendation in his fantastic course. It is quite different in nature from what I will be recommending because in some of our lines the bishop is better placedon g7, but ...Be7 is also perfectly playable.} 
8. Nd5 {A dubious move, which allows Black to equalize immediately.} 
8. Nf6
9. Bg5
9. Qa5+
10. Bd2
10. Qd8
11. Bg5 {White does not have anything better than to repeat. If you are in a must-win situation, you can continue the game in two ways.} 
11. Bxd5
12. exd5
12. Qa5+ {12...Ne7!?is also possible and leads to a complex game after13.Bxf6gxf6.} 
13. c3
13. Qxd5
14. Bxf6
14. Qxd1+
15. Rxd1
15. gxf6 {This endgame should be equal with correct play from both sides, but in practice, White has a bad score.} 
