8. Rb8 {This fresh system will be my recommendation. To realize why we waste a tempo on ...Rb8, you need to understand the drawbacks of the most natural moves here. Now White has many continuations, and our reaction will vary greatly depending on White's moves. Sometimes we develop the bishop to e7, but in other lines, it is better placed on g7 (or even h6!).  The knight on g8 normally comes to f6, but we usually wait because we do not want to give White the option of Bg5, activating the bishop. It is also important to be able to detect when playing ...b5 is correct or not, because in some positions it can give us great activity, but in others, it can help White develop an initiative on the kingside starting with a4.  As you can see, the position is quite subtle, it's great for learning dynamic chess, and I have tried to the best of my ability to explain it.8...Rc8looks more natural, but White has9.Be3!, and the threatof Nb6 is unpleasant since our queenside would be completely paralyzed.8...b5!?9.Ne3Nf6− Shirov has played this way quite a lot. It is also perfectly playable.8...Nf6allows9.Bg5, with an improved Sveshnikov for White.} 
9. Be2 {White can develop the light-squared bishop to a more modest square.Here,9...Nf6allows10.Bg5!With the bishop on d3, this was perfectly fine for Black, but now after10...Be711.Bxf6!, we cannot take the bishop because White can take the pawn with check and we are worse. So, we start with 9...Be7.} 
9. Be7
10. O-O
10. Nf6
11. Ne3 {It is strange to go for this plan with the bishop on e2.} 
11. O-O {The natural follow-up is Ncd5, but now the pawn is hanging. In the game Szadkowski-Srdanovic, chess.com 2020, White played:} 
12. Bf3 {12.Ned5Bxd513.exd5Nd4is also very nice for Black.} 
12. Nd4 {We gain the bishop pair and stand slightly better already.} 
