8. Rb8 {This fresh system will be my recommendation. To realize why we waste a tempo on ...Rb8, you need to understand the drawbacks of the most natural moves here. Now White has many continuations, and our reaction will vary greatly depending on White's moves. Sometimes we develop the bishop to e7, but in other lines, it is better placed on g7 (or even h6!).  The knight on g8 normally comes to f6, but we usually wait because we do not want to give White the option of Bg5, activating the bishop. It is also important to be able to detect when playing ...b5 is correct or not, because in some positions it can give us great activity, but in others, it can help White develop an initiative on the kingside starting with a4.  As you can see, the position is quite subtle, it's great for learning dynamic chess, and I have tried to the best of my ability to explain it.8...Rc8looks more natural, but White has9.Be3!, and the threatof Nb6 is unpleasant since our queenside would be completely paralyzed.8...b5!?9.Ne3Nf6− Shirov has played this way quite a lot. It is also perfectly playable.8...Nf6allows9.Bg5, with an improved Sveshnikov for White.} 
9. Be3 {A very interesting move. If we play9...b5,White's idea is to put the knight on d2 and then try to play against our weakened queenside,and if9...Nf6, then10.Bg5!?is very interesting. Here I hesitated about what to recommend, but in the end, I decided to go for the most intuitive way of playing.} 
9. b5 {The most forcing solution.} 
10. Nd2
10. f5 {I have decided in the end to recommend this move.10...Nf6is possible, but11.a4!leads by force to positions where White has very easy play. 10...f5 adds more tension to the position.} 
11. exf5
11. Bxf5
12. Qf3
12. Qd7
13. Nde4
13. Nb4 {We are trying to make White castle, when our counterplay will be strong. Moves like14.Rc1or14.Bd3are of course not ideal for White. Beware that after14.O-O-O, the position gets quite crazy but since10...f5!?is a novelty, I find it quite unlikely that White players will be well prepared here, so I recommend playing over the following sample lines to get a feeling for the position.} 
14. O-O-O
14. Nf6
15. Nxf6+
15. gxf6
16. Ne4
16. Be7 {Now we are ready to play ...d5, so White has to do something fast.} 
17. Bc5
17. Bxe4 {This is also decent. The machine says White is slightly better after the following semi-forced sequence though.} 
18. Qxe4
18. f5 {A nice trick!} 
19. Qf3 {19.Qxb4dxc5is the point.} 
19. Nxa2+
20. Kb1
20. Qe6
21. Ba7
21. Nb4
22. Qa3
22. Rb7
23. Qxb4
23. Rxa7
24. Qa5 {I find it very hard to believe that White is better. We are a pawn up at the moment, and it is not clear why we should be worse here.} 
