12. g3 {This pawn sacrifice is the recommendation of Saric. White wants to get a strong grip on the light squares after Black takes on d5. I think I have found a nice solution for Black's problems here.} 
12. Nbxd5
13. Bg2
13. Nc7 {The knight is safer on c7. Next, we want to play ...e4 and ...d5 to increase our control on the light squares. After13...Nb614.Ne3, White hasalso a5 ideas, and we are not in time to mobilize our center.} 
14. Qe2 {White stops our ...e4 idea, but Qe2 is not particularly useful for White's plans and we get nice play.} 
14. Be7
15. O-O
15. O-O {15...e4?!looks tempting but after16.Nd2(16.Bxe4?d5is the idea)16...d517.Rd1!Qc818.c4⩲, we are under pressure.} 
16. Rd1 {16.Bg5e4!White cannot takeon e4, and next, we play ...d5 with a good position.} 
16. Re8 {Eyeing White's queen.} 
17. Be3 {17.Nxe5?Bf8is the pointof ...Re8.} 
17. d5 {The most forcing solution, although17...Bf8is also possible.} 
18. Nxe5
18. Bd6
19. Ng4 {The point of17...d5is that White has to bring the knight to this strange square. Black is better after both19.Nf3?!Ng4!and19.Nd3d4!} 
19. Ne4 {Now we are threatening to trap the knight and White has to weaken the position to stop this.} 
20. f3
20. Nc5
21. Qf2
21. Nd7 {White's pieces are misplaced and we have an interesting middlegame.} 
