14. O-O
14. e4 {Now White has to do something quickly or will be down a pawn with no compensation. The games get a forcing nature, but the ideas are quite simple and you do not have to memorize everything.} 
15. a5 {Probably the strongest move, but quite difficult to understand in an OTB game. White wants to put the knight on b6 and take it from there.} 
15. d5 {Black reinforces the pawn on e4 and is getting ready to develop the last minor piece in order to castle.} 
16. Nb6
16. Bc5
17. Bf4
17. O-O
18. Be5 {Threatening to win the exchange with Bxf6 and Nd7.18.c4d4transposes to the 17.c4 variation.} 
18. Nd7 {There are other moves like18...Kh8, but this is the most uncomplicated solution.} 
19. Bxc7
19. Qxc7
20. Nxd5 {20.Nxd7Qxd721.Bxe4Rfd8is completely equal.} 
20. Qe5 {It looks like Black is perfectly okay with a fine bishop on c5. At low depths, the machine insists White has pressure, but as we will see the human evaluation is actually the correct one.} 
21. b4
21. Ba7
22. c4
22. Rbd8
23. Qc2
23. f5 {Next, we want to exchange knights and play ...e3 if we are allowed.} 
24. Rad1
24. Nf6
25. Nxf6+
25. Qxf6
26. c5 {This is Stockfish's idea. If we do not play with care, White will play f3 and after the exchange, our pawns on the queenside will be very weak. But we have another source of counterplay in that case: the ...f4 push.} 
26. g6 {A nice prophylactic idea since White is intending to push f3 and open the f-file. After this and also an eventual rook trade on d8, the f5-pawn could be suffering. It also gives the black king the g7-square, which is the best place to go after a possible check on the g8-a2 diagonal.} 
27. f3
27. Rxd1
28. Rxd1
28. Bb8
29. fxe4
29. f4 {Black has lots of counterplay.} 
