1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. N1c3
6. a6
7. Na3
7. Be6 {7...Be7is King's recommendation in his fantastic course. It is quite different in nature from what I will be recommending because in some of our lines the bishop is better placedon g7, but ...Be7 is also perfectly playable.} 
8. Nc4
8. Rb8 {This fresh system will be my recommendation. To realize why we waste a tempo on ...Rb8, you need to understand the drawbacks of the most natural moves here. Now White has many continuations, and our reaction will vary greatly depending on White's moves. Sometimes we develop the bishop to e7, but in other lines, it is better placed on g7 (or even h6!).  The knight on g8 normally comes to f6, but we usually wait because we do not want to give White the option of Bg5, activating the bishop. It is also important to be able to detect when playing ...b5 is correct or not, because in some positions it can give us great activity, but in others, it can help White develop an initiative on the kingside starting with a4.  As you can see, the position is quite subtle, it's great for learning dynamic chess, and I have tried to the best of my ability to explain it.8...Rc8looks more natural, but White has9.Be3!, and the threatof Nb6 is unpleasant since our queenside would be completely paralyzed.8...b5!?9.Ne3Nf6− Shirov has played this way quite a lot. It is also perfectly playable.8...Nf6allows9.Bg5, with an improved Sveshnikov for White.} 
9. a4 {A very critical continuation, recommended by Saric in his great Chessable course against the Sicilian. White stops ...b5 for good and waits for ...Nf6 to happen, when Bg5 is unpleasant. But a4 also has a drawback: it weakens the b4-square significantly. We can take advantage of that!} 
9. Nb4 {9...Nf610.Bg5!Nb411.Bxf6Qxf612.Ne3⩲is playable, but it is a worse version than some positions we have seen in the9.Be2and9.Bd3lines because our queen is misplacedon f6 and we will probably have to go ...Qd8 followed by ...Be7, when we have lost quite a few tempi. Black's position was slightly worse in ½-½ Vitiugov-Maghsoodloo, chess.com 2020.} 
10. Nd5 {The most logical and also the most critical.} 
10. Bxd5 {It is important to take with the bishop and put pressure on the d5-pawn.After10...Nxd5?!11.exd5Bf512.Bd3Bxd313.Qxd3⩲, White is quite fast on the queenside, and we have not even castled yet.} 
11. exd5
11. Nf6
12. g3 {This pawn sacrifice is the recommendation of Saric. White wants to get a strong grip on the light squares after Black takes on d5. I think I have found a nice solution for Black's problems here.} 
12. Nbxd5
