9. Bxd5 {After9...b510.Nce3Nf611.Bd3Be712.O-OO-O, White has pressure on the queenside because we have created a hookwith ...b5.9...Nf610.Bg5−the general rule in this repertoire is that we do not allow these quick Bg5s.10...Bxd511.exd5Ne712.Bxf6gxf613.a4. These positions look very dangerous for Black, where White has domination on the light squares.} 
10. exd5 {10.Qxd5?would be a big mistake due to10...Nd4and White has to be careful not to lose immediately.} 
10. Nce7
11. g3
11. b5 {We have seen that we have to be very careful making this move without the light-squared bishop, but now it is the right moment.} 
12. Ne3
12. g6
13. c4 {This move is possible, but our plans do not change.} 
13. Bh6
14. cxb5
14. axb5
15. Bh3 {15.Qb3does not change anything.} 
15. f5
16. O-O
16. Nf6 {We have an easy game. Just make sure that after, for instance,17.Re1you don't fall for17...O-O18.Nxf5!Nxf519.Bxf5and now we don't have time for19...Bxc1because of20.Be6+, which comes with tempo. Instead,17...Kf8!?followed by ...Kg7 is a viable alternative.} 
