12. a4 {It is very unlikely an opponent without preparation will play like this. The point behind the move is actually quite deep and we can only understand it after looking at the immediate12.g5.} 
12. h6
13. h4
13. Rc8 {The rook has done its job, and it takes a better position attacking White's knight. Now the knight is touched, and White cannot play Bg2. This position has never been reached, but I believe it is critical for the whole 8...Rb8 line, so I have analyzed it quite deeply.13...Nexd514.Bg2Nb615.Ne3is similar to the 9.a4 line,but here the h4-g4 tandem gives White a better version.} 
14. Qf3
14. Nfxd5 {It is better to take with this knight.14...Nexd5?!is a worse version for Black.The reason is that in many cases, White would be threatening g5.15.Bd2!,covering b4.15...Qd716.Rg1±followed by O-O-O and white is better.} 
15. Bd2
15. Qd7 {Prophylaxis against O-O-O and Qb3.} 
16. Ba5 {White improves the bishop and prepares to castle queenside.} 
16. h5 {A very important detail! In many lines, including ...h5 and g5 is good for us because we can get counterplay with the pawn lever ...f6!} 
17. g5 {17.gxh5Rh6!followed by ...Rf6 with counterplay.} 
17. Nf4
18. Qxb7 {A nice tactical trick − fortunately, the c2-pawn is hanging at the end of the line.} 
18. Qxb7
19. Nxd6+
19. Kd7
20. Nxb7
20. Rxc2
21. Bxa6
21. Ned5
22. O-O
22. Be7 {It turns out White cannot keep the extra pawn because the pieces are on very bad squares.} 
23. b4
23. Bxb4
24. Bb5+
24. Ke7
25. Bxb4+ {If White tries25.Rfc1instead, Black can opt for the restrained25...Rxc1+26.Rxc1Bxa527.Nxa5f6, with an equal endgame, or go for the more forcing25...Rhc8, when after26.Rxc2Rxc227.Bxb4+Nxb428.a5Nh3+, Black has enough resources to keep the balance. For instance,29.Kg2can be met by29...Nxf230.a6Ng4+31.Kg1Nh232.a7Nf3+33.Kf1Nh2+and a draw is inevitable.} 
25. Nxb4
26. Rfd1
26. Nc6 {A possible continuation is27.Rac1Rxc128.Rxc1Rb8(the knight is not hanging on c6 due to ...Ne2+)29.a5Nxa530.Rc7+Kf831.Nd6Kg8=, with an equal endgame.} 
