[White "16) Kalashnikov 6.c4 g6 7.Bd3"]
[Black "Informational − Various 6th Moves for Black"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. c4 {In this chapter we will be looking at one of the most popular continuations,6.c4. This move brings White more control overthe d5-square, so our typical Kalasnikhov breakthrough with ...d5 will be harder to achieve than in the lines we have seen with6.N1c3.The main drawback of c4 is that it weakens the d4-square, and we will see that in some lines the pawn on c4 can also become a weakness. 6.c4 is recommended by GM Miguel Santos in his excellent Sicilian course, so we have to study it carefully.} 
6. Be6 {This is the move suggested by King in his excellent Kalashnikov course. His idea is also to play with ...g6, so sometimes it will transpose to our lines, but I think this move order is slightly inaccurate because of the following line.6...Be7is the old way of playing, but I do not like it too much. Black's idea is to exchange the dark-squared bishops, but I think that with theweakness on d6, we should try to maintain as many pieces on the board as we can and play in an active way.6...a6was our reaction against 6.N1c3, but here it is a small mistake.7.N5c3!This is the problem with ...a6: White does not need many tempi to play Nd5 and Nbc3, to get total control of d5. A good rule of thumb is Black plays ...a6 only when the knight on b1 has already been developed to c3.} 
7. Bd3 {This is not so popular, but it is what Santos recommends.} 
7. Nf6
8. O-O
8. g6
9. N5c3 {The problem with this move order.9.N1c3a610.Na3Bg7actually transposes to our repertoire,but White is able to achieve the perfect setup with Nd5 and Nbc3 very quickly with this move.} 
9. Bg7
10. Nd5 {Now we can understand why we don't want to develop the bishop to e6 too early: it is not possible to take with the knight because we lose a piece.} 
10. O-O {10...Bxd5is probably the best move but after11.cxd5Nd412.Nc3, White has the bishop pair, more space, and is playing for two results.} 
11. Nbc3
11. Nd7
12. Be3
12. Nd4
13. Qd2
13. Rc8
14. Bg5 {This is the key move for White in this line.} 
14. f6
15. Be3 {White now threatens to take on d4 and Ne2, when it will be difficult to defend the d4-pawn because the pawn on f6 is misplaced.} 
15. f5
16. exf5
16. gxf5
17. Rae1 {White has all the pieces prepared for a central break with f4. This is why I think that starting with6...g6is better.} 
