7. Nf6 {Once again, it is very important to get the move orders right.7...Bg7would allow8.Be2!and White is takingwith a check on d6.} 
8. O-O
8. Bg7 {This is the most natural move, but now White can capture our d6 pawn in a number of ways. We will see that the d4-square and our better development will compensate for it.} 
9. Bc2 {The most natural retreat for the bishop − from c2, the bishop defends e4.} 
9. O-O {Active play! White can take on d6 in two different ways, and we will get sufficient compensation thanks to our better development and the d4-square.} 
10. b3 {The idea is to take on d6 and have Ba3 to protect the knight, but it simply does not work.} 
10. a6
11. Nxd6
11. Bg4 {Always a good idea in these positions since f3 is detrimental for White's position.} 
12. f3
12. Be6
13. Ba3
13. b5 {Threatening ...b4.} 
14. cxb5
14. Qb6+
15. Kh1
15. axb5 {Suddenly, White is completely lost. The computer already screams -3, as there is just no way to save all the loose pieces.} 
