9. Bc2 {The most natural retreat for the bishop − from c2, the bishop defends e4.} 
9. O-O {Active play! White can take on d6 in two different ways, and we will get sufficient compensation thanks to our better development and the d4-square.} 
10. Qxd6
10. Be6 {Now White has many different moves, but our ideas are always the same: quick development and going for the ...b5 counterplay! You do not have to memorize the following variations, but looking at them will give you a feeling for the position.} 
11. N1a3
11. Nd4 {Like against 11.b3, here11...Qc8is also a good move,planning ...Rd8 and ...Nh5.} 
12. Qxd8
12. Rfxd8 {Why take with this rook? Because the other one is protecting the a7-pawn and besides that, the ideal locations for the rooks are c8 and d8 since these files are the only open and semi-open ones.} 
