6. g6 {This move has received the seal of approval of Giri and David Anton. We want to play a setup with ...g6, ...Nf6, ...Bg7, ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...O-O, and ...a6, but it is very important to get the move orders right.  We use the above order, but we should always be on the lookout for exceptions. For instance:  we play ...a6 as soon as White plays N1c3, to force the knight on b5 to retreat to a3; we play ...Nf6 as soon as White plays h4 in order to prevent h5. The main reason for delaying ...Nf6 is to keep the option of playing ...f5 alive.Note that we start with6...g6!because after6...Be6, we allow7.Bd3!, which is GM Santos's recommendation.} 
7. Bd3 {The move recommended both by Santos and Shaw. It is very tricky: White just makes useful developing moves without playing N1c3.If we play7...a6, then White gets perfect coordination with8.N5c3followed by Nd5 and N1c3 much faster than in the lines with N1c3, when the b5-knight goes to a3 and c2 and has to waste much more time to reach a decent square. 7.Bd3 is not very popular at the moment, but I expect it to become very trendy so I recommend you study this chapter carefully.} 
7. Nf6 {Once again, it is very important to get the move orders right.7...Bg7would allow8.Be2!and White is takingwith a check on d6.} 
8. O-O
8. Bg7 {This is the most natural move, but now White can capture our d6 pawn in a number of ways. We will see that the d4-square and our better development will compensate for it.} 
9. Be2
9. O-O {9...Nxe410.Bf3is good for White,but again, we can sacrifice the d6-pawn and get good play.} 
10. N1c3 {10.Qxd6?With the bishop on c2, this made sense, but now White just loses the e4-pawn.} 
10. Be6
11. Be3 {11.Nxd6transposes to the 10.Nxd6 line.White says there is no hurry to take our d6-pawn, but we are basically going to force that with our next move.} 
11. a6 {Always strive for active play! Moves like11...Ne8should not even cross our minds.} 
12. Nxd6 {12.Na3Nd4is fine for Black, as we have an improved version of the main line with the knightalready on d4.} 
12. Nd4
13. Bxd4
13. exd4
14. Qxd4
14. Nxe4 {A nice shot, allowing us to equalize.} 
15. Qxe4
15. Qxd6 {We are a pawn down, but the position is open and we are going to put pressure on White's queenside. The machine says 0.00 of course. :)} 
