1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. c4 {In this chapter we will be looking at one of the most popular continuations,6.c4. This move brings White more control overthe d5-square, so our typical Kalasnikhov breakthrough with ...d5 will be harder to achieve than in the lines we have seen with6.N1c3.The main drawback of c4 is that it weakens the d4-square, and we will see that in some lines the pawn on c4 can also become a weakness. 6.c4 is recommended by GM Miguel Santos in his excellent Sicilian course, so we have to study it carefully.} 
6. g6 {This move has received the seal of approval of Giri and David Anton. We want to play a setup with ...g6, ...Nf6, ...Bg7, ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...O-O, and ...a6, but it is very important to get the move orders right.  We use the above order, but we should always be on the lookout for exceptions. For instance:  we play ...a6 as soon as White plays N1c3, to force the knight on b5 to retreat to a3; we play ...Nf6 as soon as White plays h4 in order to prevent h5. The main reason for delaying ...Nf6 is to keep the option of playing ...f5 alive.Note that we start with6...g6!because after6...Be6, we allow7.Bd3!, which is GM Santos's recommendation.} 
7. Bd3 {The move recommended both by Santos and Shaw. It is very tricky: White just makes useful developing moves without playing N1c3.If we play7...a6, then White gets perfect coordination with8.N5c3followed by Nd5 and N1c3 much faster than in the lines with N1c3, when the b5-knight goes to a3 and c2 and has to waste much more time to reach a decent square. 7.Bd3 is not very popular at the moment, but I expect it to become very trendy so I recommend you study this chapter carefully.} 
7. Nf6 {Once again, it is very important to get the move orders right.7...Bg7would allow8.Be2!and White is takingwith a check on d6.} 
8. O-O
8. Bg7 {This is the most natural move, but now White can capture our d6 pawn in a number of ways. We will see that the d4-square and our better development will compensate for it.} 
9. Be2
9. O-O {9...Nxe410.Bf3is good for White,but again, we can sacrifice the d6-pawn and get good play.} 
10. Nxd6 {10.Qxd6?With the bishop on c2, this made sense, but now White just loses the e4-pawn.} 
10. Be6
11. Nc3
11. Nd4 {11...a612.Be3Nd4would transpose, but the issue with this move order is that it hands White an additional option:12.c5!and now12...Nd4is well met by13.Bc4, with a preferable position for White.} 
12. Ndb5
12. Rc8 {This move looks innocent, but the attack on the c4-pawn is not so easy to parry.} 
13. Na3 {The only reasonable way of defending the c4-pawn.} 
13. a6
14. Be3
14. Re8 {I like this move a lot: we want to put more pressure on the c4-pawn and activate our worst piece at the same time with ...Bf8.} 
15. f3 {This is more natural than15.Bd3, but it weakens the dark squares a lot.} 
15. Bf8
16. Nd5
16. Bxa3
17. Bxd4
17. exd4
18. bxa3
18. b5
19. Qxd4
19. Nxd5
20. cxd5
20. Bxd5 {The position is equal. White's extra pawn is not meaningful here.} 
