4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. c4 {In this chapter we will be looking at one of the most popular continuations,6.c4. This move brings White more control overthe d5-square, so our typical Kalasnikhov breakthrough with ...d5 will be harder to achieve than in the lines we have seen with6.N1c3.The main drawback of c4 is that it weakens the d4-square, and we will see that in some lines the pawn on c4 can also become a weakness. 6.c4 is recommended by GM Miguel Santos in his excellent Sicilian course, so we have to study it carefully.} 
6. g6 {This move has received the seal of approval of Giri and David Anton. We want to play a setup with ...g6, ...Nf6, ...Bg7, ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...O-O, and ...a6, but it is very important to get the move orders right.  We use the above order, but we should always be on the lookout for exceptions. For instance:  we play ...a6 as soon as White plays N1c3, to force the knight on b5 to retreat to a3; we play ...Nf6 as soon as White plays h4 in order to prevent h5. The main reason for delaying ...Nf6 is to keep the option of playing ...f5 alive.Note that we start with6...g6!because after6...Be6, we allow7.Bd3!, which is GM Santos's recommendation.} 
7. N1c3 {The most common move.} 
7. a6 {Now we can play this because the knight is already on c3.} 
8. Na3
8. Bg7
9. h4 {A very natural move when we play with ...g6, but now we are well-prepared to meet it.} 
9. Nf6
10. Be2
10. Nd4 {An improvement over the game Ponkratov-Khanin, where after10...h511.Bg5!, Black was under some pressure. We can play more dynamically andavoid h5 in a more active way.} 
11. Nc2
11. O-O {We should not refrain from this typical sacrifice.} 
12. Nxd4
12. exd4
13. Qxd4
13. Re8
14. Bg5 {White's best bet, but losing the dark-squared bishop does not usually bring happiness to White in the Kalashnikov.} 
14. h6
15. Bxf6
15. Bxf6
16. Qd3
16. Be6 {Here we have two options that give good compensation: we can try the text move, adding pressure on the c4-pawn, or we can play16...Bxc3+, forcing White to take with the pawn, and then put pressure on the c-file. We have full compensation for the pawn with both moves and it is a matter of taste which one to choose.} 
