6. g6 {This move has received the seal of approval of Giri and David Anton. We want to play a setup with ...g6, ...Nf6, ...Bg7, ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...O-O, and ...a6, but it is very important to get the move orders right.  We use the above order, but we should always be on the lookout for exceptions. For instance:  we play ...a6 as soon as White plays N1c3, to force the knight on b5 to retreat to a3; we play ...Nf6 as soon as White plays h4 in order to prevent h5. The main reason for delaying ...Nf6 is to keep the option of playing ...f5 alive.Note that we start with6...g6!because after6...Be6, we allow7.Bd3!, which is GM Santos's recommendation.} 
7. N1c3 {The most common move.} 
7. a6 {Now we can play this because the knight is already on c3.} 
8. Na3
8. Bg7
9. Nc2
9. Be6 {Now White has three main ideas:  ♟ Develop the bishop to e2 (it avoids ...Ng4 ideas) and continue with normal moves like O-O, Be3, and Qd2.  ♟ Develop the bishop to d3 and continue with normal moves. The dark-squared bishop is more difficult to develop for White in this line because after Be3 we can always go ...Ng4!  ♟ Try to put pressure on the d6-pawn with Be3, Qd2, O-O-O or Rd1.} 
10. Bd3
10. Nf6 {I believe f6 is the best square for Black's knight almost always in these lines.10...Nh6is sometimes interesting when the bishopis on e3 because we can try to hit it with ...Ng4, but here White can use the fact that the rook is still on h1 and play the powerful11.h4!when the position suddenly gets very dangerous for Black.} 
11. O-O
11. Rc8
12. Bg5 {Threatening Nd5, which forces ...h6. White has 2 basic plans after this move: retreating to h4 or retreating to e3.} 
12. h6
13. Be3 {This is very similar to12.Be3,the only difference being that our pawn is on h6 instead of h7. We lose the ...Bh6 plans, but our pawn on h6 can be useful in some lines.} 
13. Ng4
14. Bd2
14. O-O
15. Nd5 {In case of15.h3Nf616.Nd5Nd7, we almost transpose to the 12.Be3 variation as explained above.} 
15. f5
16. f3
16. Nf6 {Now White has many decent moves, so it is important to understand the position. We have 2 plans: ...f4 followed by ...g5 in King's Indian style, or trying to employ the plans with ...fxe4, ...Nd7, ...Bxd5,  and ...Nd4.} 
17. b4 {This is already an inaccuracy.} 
17. Bxd5
18. cxd5
18. fxe4
19. fxe4
19. Nd4
20. Nxd4
20. exd4 {White's bishop pair is not useful here and our knight on e5 will be magnificent.} 
