[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6 {This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central square on d4.} 
3. d4
3. cxd4
4. Nxd4
4. e5 {Going for the Kalashnikov Variation. Pros: we gain a tempo by kicking the white knight on d4. Cons: the d5-square will be weak for the rest of the game. This leads to unbalanced and complex positions!} 
5. Nb5
5. d6 {This move is very important, stopping Nd6+ when White would be getting the bishop pair already.} 
6. c4 {In this chapter we will be looking at one of the most popular continuations,6.c4. This move brings White more control overthe d5-square, so our typical Kalasnikhov breakthrough with ...d5 will be harder to achieve than in the lines we have seen with6.N1c3.The main drawback of c4 is that it weakens the d4-square, and we will see that in some lines the pawn on c4 can also become a weakness. 6.c4 is recommended by GM Miguel Santos in his excellent Sicilian course, so we have to study it carefully.} 
6. g6 {This move has received the seal of approval of Giri and David Anton. We want to play a setup with ...g6, ...Nf6, ...Bg7, ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...O-O, and ...a6, but it is very important to get the move orders right.  We use the above order, but we should always be on the lookout for exceptions. For instance:  we play ...a6 as soon as White plays N1c3, to force the knight on b5 to retreat to a3; we play ...Nf6 as soon as White plays h4 in order to prevent h5. The main reason for delaying ...Nf6 is to keep the option of playing ...f5 alive.Note that we start with6...g6!because after6...Be6, we allow7.Bd3!, which is GM Santos's recommendation.} 
7. N1c3 {The most common move.} 
7. a6 {Now we can play this because the knight is already on c3.} 
8. Na3
8. Bg7
9. Nc2
9. Be6 {Now White has three main ideas:  ♟ Develop the bishop to e2 (it avoids ...Ng4 ideas) and continue with normal moves like O-O, Be3, and Qd2.  ♟ Develop the bishop to d3 and continue with normal moves. The dark-squared bishop is more difficult to develop for White in this line because after Be3 we can always go ...Ng4!  ♟ Try to put pressure on the d6-pawn with Be3, Qd2, O-O-O or Rd1.} 
10. Be2 {From here the bishop does not block White's queen and the dark-squared bishop will be more stable on e3 because ...Ng4 will be more difficult to achieve.} 
10. Nf6
11. O-O
11. Rc8 {11...O-Ois also decent and actually should transpose if White plays12.Be3,but ...Rc8 gives us extra options if White develops the bishop to g5 as we will see.} 
12. Be3
12. O-O {12...Na5?looks tempting, but we are much worse after13.b3b514.Nd5!Threatening Bb6. We should not allow this, so we simply castle instead.14...bxc4(14...Bxd515.exd5bxc416.b4+-)15.Bb6+-.} 
13. b3 {This natural move allows us to execute our typical break.} 
13. b5 {The knight on c3 is unprotected.} 
14. cxb5
14. axb5 {14...Ne7!?was played in the famous game Anand-Maghsoodloo, but14...axb5is better from the theoretical point of view.} 
15. Bxb5
15. Na7 {Cheparinov won a beautiful game after15...Ne7, although it is not totally correct.} 
16. Bxa7
16. Rxc3 {White has many pieces in the air.} 
17. Bd3
17. Qa8
18. Be3
18. Nxe4 {White's pawns are very far away from queening, and our central control is much more important here. We are almost winning.} 
